This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

  ```c#
   internal class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
        }

        static void Test(dynamic obj)
        {
            if (obj is string str1)
                Console.WriteLine(str1); // No problem
            if (Check(obj) && obj is string str2)
                Console.WriteLine(str2); // Use of unassigned local variable
        }

        static bool Check(dynamic obj) => true;
    }
```

**Version Used**: Appears to have first become an issue in .NET7, still present in .NET8.

Fundamentally, a cast from a `nint` pointer returned from a native function (for example by marshalling using a SafeHandle implementation), where the top bit is set, causes an OverflowException when casting to `void*`, when `CheckForOverflowUnderflow` is enabled in the project.

This issue has been noticed on 32-bit architectures, because that's the only time I've seen the top bit of a pointer set, but could still happen on 64-bit.

In my mind, casts from `nint` to `void*` should not apply a checked cast and trigger an OverflowException. Even when `CheckForOverflowUnderflow` is specified, because a negative `nint` value is absolutely a valid `void*`.

Manual pinvoke means this isn't a huge issue for us (can always use nuint as a return type); but `SafeHandle` uses nint as its handle type, which means the issue happens reliably if marshalling a returned pointer using `SafeHandle`, then casting the wrapped `SafeHandle.handle` to a `void*`. Workaround is to call `nint.ToPointer()` instead, which is defined in the runtime library that does not have `CheckForOverflowUnderflow` set.

The problem comes down to this generated IL (a custom function in a SafeHandle derived class that casts the `nint` to a pointer) differing between .NET8 and .NET 6:

.NET 8:
```csharp
// .method public hidebysig instance void*
  // GetPointer() cil managed
public unsafe void* GetPointer()
// .maxstack 8
// 
// IL_0000: ldarg.0      // this
// IL_0001: ldfld        native int [System.Runtime]System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle::handle
// IL_0006: conv.ovf.u
// IL_0007: ret
// 
{
  return (void*) checked ((UIntPtr) this.handle);
}
```

.NET 6
```csharp
// .method public hidebysig instance void*
  // GetPointer() cil managed
public unsafe void* GetPointer()
// .maxstack 8
// 
// IL_0000: ldarg.0      // this
// IL_0001: ldfld        native int [System.Runtime]System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle::handle
// IL_0006: call         void* [System.Runtime]System.IntPtr::op_Explicit(native int)
// IL_000b: ret
// 
{
  return (void*) this.handle;
}
```

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Enable CheckForOverflowUnderflow in the csproj.
2. Get a pointer that has the top bit set. In my case, this was discovered and recreated by using mmap with `MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS` flags. But any invoke function that returns a pointer that ends up as a negative `nint` will suffice.
3. Cast the nint to void*.
4. OverflowException.

Here's a repo that uses mmap to prove the problem; you can run `dotnet publish -c Release -f net8.0 -r linux-arm` to get a 32-bit ARM binary, which reliably reproduces the problem.

https://github.com/enclave-alistair/RoslynPointerCastingWithCheckedArithmetic

I can't provide SharpLab frustratingly, because there's no way to enable CheckForOverflowUnderflow.

**Expected Behavior**:

- Casting any number to `void*` should not trigger a checked cast, even with `CheckForOverflowUnderflow` switched on.

**Actual Behavior**:

- Casting a number, including nint, to `void*`, triggers a checked cast, and can fail with `CheckForOverflowUnderflow`.

**Version Used**: 
Version 17.11.0 Preview 1.0 [34804.211.main]

**Steps to Reproduce**:
```C#
using System.Collections;

MyCollection<object> c = new() { "Hello" };

class MyCollection<T> : IEnumerable<T[]>
{
    public void Add(T item) { }
    public IEnumerator<T[]> GetEnumerator() => throw new NotImplementedException();
    IEnumerator IEnumerable.GetEnumerator() => GetEnumerator();
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:
IDE0028

**Expected Behavior**:
No diagnostics.

**Actual Behavior**:
IDE0028 triggers and the fixer rewrites the `new() { "Hello" }` to be `["Hello"]`, which then fails to compile with `error CS0029: Cannot implicitly convert type 'string' to 'object[]'`.

